Task 1: Extract and Remove Image Metadata with ExifTool
Step 1.1: Setup Working Environment
Create a structured directory for lab activities:

# Create directory structure
mkdir -p ~/metadata_lab/{original,cleaned,scripts}
cd ~/metadata_lab

# Verify ExifTool installation
exiftool -ver

# If not installed, run:
# sudo apt update && sudo apt install exiftool -y
Step 1.2: Analyze Image Metadata
Download or create sample images and examine their metadata:

# Navigate to original directory
cd ~/metadata_lab/original

# Create test image (requires ImageMagick)
convert -size 800x600 xc:lightblue -font Arial -pointsize 30 \
  -draw "text 300,300 'Test Image'" test_image.jpg

# Extract all metadata
exiftool test_image.jpg

# Extract specific fields
exiftool -GPS* -CreateDate -ModifyDate test_image.jpg

# Export metadata to JSON
exiftool -json test_image.jpg > metadata_report.json

# View JSON output
cat metadata_report.json
Step 1.3: Remove Metadata from Images
Practice different metadata removal techniques:

# Method 1: Remove all metadata (creates backup)
exiftool -all= test_image.jpg

# Restore from backup for next test
mv test_image.jpg_original test_image.jpg

# Method 2: Remove without backup
exiftool -all= -overwrite_original test_image.jpg

# Method 3: Remove specific fields only
exiftool -GPS:all= -EXIF:CreateDate= -overwrite_original test_image.jpg

# Method 4: Clean and save to different directory
exiftool -all= -o ../cleaned/ test_image.jpg

# Verify removal
exiftool ../cleaned/test_image.jpg
Step 1.4: Batch Process Multiple Images
Process multiple files simultaneously:

# Create multiple test images
for i in {1..5}; do
  convert -size 640x480 xc:lightgreen -pointsize 20 \
    -draw "text 250,240 'Image $i'" image_$i.jpg
done

# Remove metadata from all JPEG files
exiftool -all= -overwrite_original *.jpg

# Process specific file types recursively
exiftool -all= -overwrite_original -ext jpg -ext png -r .

# Verify batch processing
exiftool -T -filename -filesize *.jpg
